default44.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe 
defaultResearch Excellence Framework
default (REF
default)
default promotes equality and diversity in research careers in a number of ways.
default 
default HEIs are strongly encourage
defaultd to submit the excellent research of all eligible staff; individuals whose circumstances have constrained their ability to undertake research are able to submit fewer outputs without penalty in the assessment. 
default 
defaultEach HEI is also required to develop, document and apply a code of practice on the fair and transparent selection of staff for their REF submission. In addition,
default&#xa0;
defaultthe quality of the research environment will be assessed as part of submissions to the REF; ea
defaultch submission will be required to provide evidence as to how the submitted unit promotes equality and diversity. 
default 
defaultBy including equality and diversity measures as part of the assessment process, universities and research institutions are required to conside
defaultr them as an integral part of their research work.
default&#xa0;
default45.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe measures to promote equality and diversity through the REF have been informed by a review of the equality measures taken in the 2008 RAE, and by the work of the REF Equalities and Diversity Advisory G
defaultroup, which was established specifically to provide expert advice on the development of equality and diversity measures in the REF
default.
default&#xa0;
default46.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIn January 2013 Research Councils UK set out the expectation that equality and diversity should be embedded at all levels a
defaults part of good research practice. Those institut
defaultions
default in receipt of research funding will be expected to provide evidence of ways in which equality and diversity issues are managed at both an institutional and departmental level. This evidence can include p
defaultarticipation in schemes such as Athena Swan or Project Juno
default.  F
defaultunding is not contingent on formal accreditation requirement. 
