default people of the range of careers
default defaultthat science and technical qualifications offer and provid
defaulte stimulating scientific activities to increase their interest in STEM subjects.
default 
default 40% of 
defaultthe 25,000 
defaultSTEM ambassadors are women. The Department of Business Innovation and Skills commissioned STEMNET to run a pilot of the STEM Ambassador programme in Higher 
defaultEducation Institutions which will report at the end of August 2013. 
default This was a result of 
defaultevidence
default 
defaultthat even at the undergraduate stage, STEM students are not fully aware of the range of opportunities available to them.  
defaultThe initial findings have been ver
defaulty positive and this project aims to help undergraduates better understand the career options available to them, including entering academia.
default&#xa0;
default51.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultGovernment also funds the National Careers Service which provides independent, impartial advice to anyone, set in 
defaultthe context of an individual’s needs and priorities. Prime Contractors for the service already operate to key performance targets which include promoting equality of opportunity.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultConclusion
default52.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe issue of a lack of women in STEM careers is particularly acu
defaultte in some disciplines.  It is a long standing problem resulting from a range of factors including some intractable ones including about unconscious bias and culture.  
default Newer career paths seen as having job satisfaction and good financial remuneration do not seem to have resulted in a significant increase in the number or women choosing the profession
default.  
defaultWomen are underrepresented in the workforce in general and this is 
defaultreplicated in the STEM sector and in academia, particularly at senior levels. Although there has been lots of progress over recent years, there is still significant work required to ensure that women, as well as other underrepresented groups, are able to a
defaultccess and progress in STEM careers both in industry and academia.
default53.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
default Over recent years a greater awareness of the issue of gender diversity have developed and the some very good practice is being undertaken to address it.  Government is taking a lead by putt
defaulting the right equality and diversity legislative framework in place and providing funding via various routes to support a diverse STEM workforce, including through the STEM Diversity Programme.
default54.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultResearch demonstrates that action is needed at all stages of t
defaulthe education and career pipeline if we are to encourage 
defaultmore people 
defaultinto STEM education and careers and then retain them within the disciplines which they trained.  Government is investing in initiatives such as the STEMNET STEM Ambassador scheme, Big Bang
default Fair and National Science and Engineering Competition, which aim to engage young people in STEM so that they are motivated to pursue a STEM career in the future.
default55.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultGovernment recognises the need to ensure that we have sufficient people entering the STEM wor
defaultkforce to maintain the UK
default’
defaults leadership in many of the STEM sectors and in scientific research. Through the Industrial Strategies, which are being developed for priority sectors, mechanisms for addressing industries’ skills needs are being designed in conju
defaultnction with relevant stakeholders. However the Government does not view people with STEM skills and qualifications working outside STEM sectors as a loss. Industry tells us that STEM skills are valued wherever they are deployed in the economy and so provid
defaulted women are making informed and active choices to move away from a STEM career we should recognise the value and contribution of the STEM skills elsewhere in the economy.
